, on the influence of the left on Hollywood, and on a fascinating man whose radicalism served as a foil for launching the political careers of two Presidents: Richard Nixon and Ronald Reagan. In vivid, marvelously detailed prose, Final Victim of the Blacklist restores this major figure to his rightful place in history as it recounts one of the most captivating episodes in twentieth century cinema and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aBlacklisting of authorsxUnited States. 0aBlacklisting of authorszUnited States. 0aCommunism and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCommunism and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDramatists, AmericanvBiographyy20th century. 0aDramatists, AmericanxBiographyx20th century. 0aDramatists, Americany20th centuryvBiography. 0aMotion picture industryxHistoryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aMotion picture industryzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aScreenwritersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aScreenwriterszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aTheaterxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aTheaterzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  a1930s.  a1940s.  a1947.  a20th century.  aamerica.  aantisemitism.  abiographical.  ablacklist.  acalifornia.  acinema.  acommunism.  acommunist party.  adirectors.  aedmund wilson.  aernest hemingway.  af scott fitzgerald.  agene kelly.  ahistorical nonfiction.  ahollywood ten.  ahollywood.  ahouse unamerican activities committee.  aimprisonment.  ainfamy.  ajohn dos passos.  ajohn howard lawson.  ajoseph mccarthy.  amccarthyism.  apolitical figures.  apolitics.  aradical politics.  ared scare.  ascreenwriters.  aunited states.  aus history.08iTitle is p